1
00:00:33,955 --> 00:00:38,944
<i>♪</i>

2
00:00:48,888 --> 00:00:51,479
[match ignition]

3
00:01:52,519 --> 00:01:54,385
[NARRATOR]
There's a story that has been

4
00:01:54,385 --> 00:01:56,818
passed down for centuries,

5
00:01:56,819 --> 00:01:58,876
from father to son.

6
00:02:00,619 --> 00:02:03,518
Legend has it a
certain man came

7
00:02:03,519 --> 00:02:06,383
to live in the
village of Gladbury.

8
00:02:07,985 --> 00:02:10,218
He was a good-hearted man,

9
00:02:10,219 --> 00:02:14,311
devoted to his
family and his craft.

10
00:02:15,285 --> 00:02:19,614
The candle maker brought
light to the entire village.

11
00:02:20,352 --> 00:02:23,051
But he longed to give them more.

12
00:02:23,052 --> 00:02:25,384
Life was hard in Gladbury,

13
00:02:25,384 --> 00:02:29,339
and the people had
become disheartened.

14
00:02:31,651 --> 00:02:34,550
[NARRATOR] Night and day,
the candle maker worked,

15
00:02:34,551 --> 00:02:39,506
pouring his heart and
his prayers into each candle.

16
00:02:39,718 --> 00:02:41,784
But on the first
Sunday of Advent,

17
00:02:41,785 --> 00:02:47,351
all he had left to give...
was a single prayer,

18
00:02:47,351 --> 00:02:54,550
not for himself, but for
Gladbury, for his son,

19
00:02:54,550 --> 00:02:58,448
and for all the sons
and daughters to come.

20
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:06,474
Silence was the only answer
he would receive that night.

21
00:03:08,150 --> 00:03:10,673
Or so it seemed.

22
00:04:03,782 --> 00:04:08,510
[NARRATOR] An angel
blessed a single candle.

23
00:04:10,215 --> 00:04:14,948
The heavenly gift was given
to the ones who needed it most,

24
00:04:14,948 --> 00:04:17,381
with the simple instruction:

25
00:04:17,381 --> 00:04:21,177
Light this and pray.

26
00:04:28,014 --> 00:04:31,646
[NARRATOR] The children
hoped for an answered prayer.

27
00:04:31,647 --> 00:04:34,980
But what they
received was a miracle.

28
00:04:34,981 --> 00:04:37,613
On Christmas Eve,
the village rejoiced

29
00:04:37,614 --> 00:04:41,047
upon hearing of
their change of fortune,

30
00:04:41,048 --> 00:04:43,547
for such things do happen.

31
00:04:43,547 --> 00:04:47,309
And from them, legends are born.

32
00:04:47,947 --> 00:04:51,447
As the tale is told,
every twenty-five years,

33
00:04:51,447 --> 00:04:54,380
the angel visits
The Haddington Chandlery,

34
00:04:54,380 --> 00:04:58,142
and every time
a prayer is answered.

35
00:05:01,613 --> 00:05:06,012
But even the greatest
stories must come to an end.

36
00:05:06,613 --> 00:05:09,879
Much has changed
in two hundred years.

37
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:13,437
In a world illuminated
by modern marvels,

38
00:05:14,013 --> 00:05:18,536
who needs the
light of a simple candle?

39
00:05:19,513 --> 00:05:24,502
[bustling about and voices]

40
00:05:26,179 --> 00:05:27,546
[YOUNG BOY]
I'm starving.

41
00:05:27,546 --> 00:05:30,341
[ABNER]
How are you'! Hello.

42
00:05:34,545 --> 00:05:35,645
[ABNER]
How we doing'! Alright?

43
00:05:35,645 --> 00:05:37,045
[DAVID]
Yeah, very good, yeah.

44
00:05:37,046 --> 00:05:39,274
Hope they'll be bringing
some more soon.

45
00:05:39,378 --> 00:05:40,978
[ABNER]
Bless you little lady.

46
00:05:40,979 --> 00:05:43,545
[GIRL]
ls it soup again'!

47
00:05:43,545 --> 00:05:45,670
[ABNER]
God bless you, sir.

48
00:05:45,846 --> 00:05:47,345
[MISS FOSTER] There's no
longer a place for you here!

49
00:05:47,345 --> 00:05:47,978
[RUTH]
Please!

50
00:05:47,979 --> 00:05:49,511
[MISS FOSTER] I'm sorry,
but there's nothing I can do.

51
00:05:49,512 --> 00:05:51,671
Orders came straight
from the top.

52
00:05:52,712 --> 00:05:54,111
[MISS FOSTER]
You should learn to keep your

53
00:05:54,112 --> 00:05:57,374
affections to yourself,
Ruth Goodchild!

54
00:06:07,945 --> 00:06:11,105
[MISS FOSTER] And don't even
think about coming back!

55
00:06:13,845 --> 00:06:15,209
[WOMAN PASSERBY]
Serves you right.

56
00:06:17,778 --> 00:06:22,006
[Ruth begins to weep]

57
00:06:23,478 --> 00:06:26,137
Abner, will you take
over for a second?

58
00:06:26,444 --> 00:06:29,035
Yes. God bless you, sir.

59
00:06:34,311 --> 00:06:39,311
[Ruth weeping]

60
00:06:39,311 --> 00:06:40,537
Hello, miss.

61
00:06:41,877 --> 00:06:43,104
Miss.

62
00:06:43,144 --> 00:06:45,007
What do you want'!

63
00:06:45,376 --> 00:06:47,172
I only mean to help.

64
00:07:04,143 --> 00:07:06,473
[DAVID] It's no Buckingham
Palace, Miss Goodchild.

65
00:07:07,210 --> 00:07:08,976
But you'll be safe here.

66
00:07:08,976 --> 00:07:11,443
And with three meals
a day, you won't go hungry.

67
00:07:11,443 --> 00:07:15,205
When the baby comes, what then'!

68
00:07:15,375 --> 00:07:16,875
Well, perhaps there's someone...

69
00:07:16,876 --> 00:07:20,308
No.There's nobody.

70
00:07:20,309 --> 00:07:22,609
Or rather there was,
but he found someone else

71
00:07:22,609 --> 00:07:24,837
and dismissed me
from work today.

72
00:07:28,008 --> 00:07:29,641
[DAVID]
Don't lose hope, miss.

73
00:07:29,642 --> 00:07:32,608
We'll find a place
for you and your baby.

74
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:05,708
[ABNER]
God bless you, sir.

75
00:08:05,708 --> 00:08:06,840
[LADY CAMDON]
Reverend Richmond?

76
00:08:06,841 --> 00:08:07,974
Friend of yours?

77
00:08:07,974 --> 00:08:09,107
I have no idea.

78
00:08:09,108 --> 00:08:10,640
God bless you.

79
00:08:10,640 --> 00:08:12,936
Reverend David Richmond.

80
00:08:13,674 --> 00:08:15,774
So you really
have left the pulpit.

81
00:08:15,774 --> 00:08:18,174
Nonsense.This is my pulpit now.

82
00:08:18,174 --> 00:08:20,873
Soup, soap, and salvation.

83
00:08:20,874 --> 00:08:23,305
And please,
I'm only known as David here.

84
00:08:23,540 --> 00:08:24,806
Have we met?

85
00:08:24,807 --> 00:08:28,306
We might have, had you not
rejected my last three letters.

86
00:08:28,307 --> 00:08:32,607
Ah, yes, Lady Camdon
of Gladbury, in the flesh.

87
00:08:32,607 --> 00:08:35,273
But I'm sorry that you've
traveled so far only

88
00:08:35,273 --> 00:08:37,805
to hear me decline your
offer once again.

89
00:08:37,806 --> 00:08:41,000
My place is here,
helping the needy.

90
00:08:42,140 --> 00:08:45,206
You, sir, have you
heard this man preach?

91
00:08:45,207 --> 00:08:46,706
Can't say that I have.

92
00:08:46,706 --> 00:08:48,806
[LADY CAMDON] Villagers
flocked to London to hear him.

93
00:08:48,806 --> 00:08:51,039
I once sat by a fisherman
who rode his boat

94
00:08:51,040 --> 00:08:53,339
twelve miles for one sermon.

95
00:08:53,339 --> 00:08:54,806
It was along time ago.

96
00:08:54,806 --> 00:08:56,362
But I'll never forget.

97
00:08:58,272 --> 00:09:01,102
David Richmond, miracle man.

98
00:09:01,172 --> 00:09:03,305
In the midst of
my own great loss,

99
00:09:03,306 --> 00:09:06,931
it was your words
that revived my faith.

100
00:09:07,806 --> 00:09:11,639
Any able bodied man
can serve a bowl of soup,

101
00:09:11,639 --> 00:09:14,605
but few men have
a gift like yours.

102
00:09:16,839 --> 00:09:20,306
My only hope is that
you choose to serve

103
00:09:20,306 --> 00:09:23,533
where your gift is needed most.

104
00:09:25,772 --> 00:09:26,872
God bless you.

105
00:09:26,872 --> 00:09:28,337
[BOY] Thank you very much, sir.

106
00:09:32,371 --> 00:09:35,269
[ABNER] Perhaps you
should think about it, David.

107
00:09:38,371 --> 00:09:41,360
[ABNER]
God bless you.Well done, sir.

108
00:09:41,705 --> 00:09:43,471
[ABNER]
That's it, take a bowl.

109
00:09:43,472 --> 00:09:45,267
Sorry.

110
00:09:49,771 --> 00:09:53,171
[DAVID] Dear Lady Camdon,
your recent visit was a

111
00:09:53,171 --> 00:09:56,970
timely reminder of
the life I left behind.

112
00:09:56,971 --> 00:09:59,603
Though tragedy has
altered my course,

113
00:09:59,604 --> 00:10:02,866
I can no longer stray from
my calling in the pulpit.

114
00:10:03,637 --> 00:10:06,269
I humbly accept the offer
to serve your parish in the

115
00:10:06,270 --> 00:10:09,202
place of the late
Reverend Pillington.

116
00:10:09,804 --> 00:10:13,836
I shall arrive in Gladbury
the Friday before Advent.

117
00:10:13,837 --> 00:10:17,031
Yours truly, David Richmond.

118
00:10:21,970 --> 00:10:22,970
[EMILY]
Come on, boy!

119
00:10:22,970 --> 00:10:25,636
Come on! Move on!

120
00:10:25,636 --> 00:10:27,370
You silly old thing. Come on!

121
00:10:27,370 --> 00:10:29,268
Move on!

122
00:10:29,703 --> 00:10:31,328
Come on!

123
00:10:34,369 --> 00:10:36,335
Might I offer you
some assistance?

124
00:10:36,336 --> 00:10:39,598
Thank you, I'm quite capable!

125
00:10:42,269 --> 00:10:44,269
Well, if it wouldn't be too
forward of me, I could--

126
00:10:44,269 --> 00:10:45,530
[EMILY]
No!

127
00:10:45,869 --> 00:10:48,427
I'm not a sack of potatoes.

128
00:10:50,169 --> 00:10:51,499
Come on!

129
00:10:52,436 --> 00:10:55,163
[EMILY]
Come on, boy. Come on!

130
00:10:57,269 --> 00:10:59,167
[EMILY]
I don't need your help.

131
00:10:59,469 --> 00:11:01,662
[DAVID]
Come on. Come on.

132
00:11:02,602 --> 00:11:04,125
Come on.

133
00:11:13,802 --> 00:11:15,468
[DAVID] And where are
you headed, miss'!

134
00:11:15,469 --> 00:11:17,035
Miss Barstow.

135
00:11:17,035 --> 00:11:19,502
I'm headed to London
by way of Gladbury.

136
00:11:19,502 --> 00:11:21,001
And the people of Gladbury,

137
00:11:21,001 --> 00:11:22,967
they allow a lady to
venture on her own'!

138
00:11:22,968 --> 00:11:25,600
It's the Christmas season.
The whole town's in a fuss.

139
00:11:25,601 --> 00:11:27,301
[DAVID] But Christmas
isn't for weeks.

140
00:11:27,302 --> 00:11:28,968
[EMILY] I take it you've
never been to Gladbury.

141
00:11:28,968 --> 00:11:30,168
Is it really so bad?

142
00:11:30,168 --> 00:11:31,634
It is.

143
00:11:31,634 --> 00:11:33,657
[DAVID]Whoa,
steady boy. Come on!

144
00:11:34,035 --> 00:11:37,467
Come on, come on, come on!

145
00:11:37,968 --> 00:11:40,367
Whoa.Whoa.

146
00:11:40,367 --> 00:11:41,633
[EMILY] Especially
this Christmas

147
00:11:41,634 --> 00:11:44,033
with the new minister
set to arrive.

148
00:11:44,034 --> 00:11:47,267
Reverend High and
Mighty from London.

149
00:11:47,267 --> 00:11:49,600
I hope they dislike
him very much.

150
00:11:49,601 --> 00:11:53,033
Thank you. I hate to be indebted
to anyone, much less a stranger.

151
00:11:53,034 --> 00:11:55,167
It's an easy debt to forgive.

152
00:11:55,167 --> 00:11:58,361
"Reverend High and
Mighty" at your service.

153
00:11:59,367 --> 00:12:02,466
Reverend. How providential.

154
00:12:02,467 --> 00:12:04,366
Oh, we shall see.

155
00:12:05,301 --> 00:12:07,500
Might you have
any words of advice?

156
00:12:07,500 --> 00:12:08,659
Yes.

157
00:12:10,800 --> 00:12:12,459
Retreat.

158
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:14,432
Walk on.

159
00:12:14,433 --> 00:12:17,099
Very well then.
I look forward to

160
00:12:17,100 --> 00:12:19,033
seeing you at
church on Sunday!

161
00:12:19,033 --> 00:12:20,666
[Emily laughs]

162
00:12:20,667 --> 00:12:22,792
Walk on.

163
00:12:28,333 --> 00:12:29,499
[EDWARD]
Thank you Ebenezer.

164
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:30,999
<i>REM Hurry up, Edward.</i>

165
00:12:30,999 --> 00:12:32,798
We don't want the new
minister thinking the

166
00:12:32,799 --> 00:12:35,856
Haddingtons are a pair
of village bumpkins.

167
00:12:36,300 --> 00:12:39,166
Codswallop my dear,
you look lovely.

168
00:12:39,166 --> 00:12:42,798
I come from a long line of
bumpkins, and I'm proud of it.

169
00:12:42,799 --> 00:12:46,322
Who wouldn't love
Gladbury at Christmas?

170
00:12:48,165 --> 00:12:49,426
[MAN]
He's here!

171
00:12:53,466 --> 00:12:54,931
[GIRLS]
There he is!

172
00:12:55,165 --> 00:12:58,790
[villagers greet David]

173
00:13:06,099 --> 00:13:07,655
[crowd gasps]

174
00:13:11,598 --> 00:13:13,264
Hello.

175
00:13:13,264 --> 00:13:15,787
[HERBERT] Alright gentlefolk,
make some space.

176
00:13:16,598 --> 00:13:18,461
Oh here, allow me.

177
00:13:20,932 --> 00:13:23,531
Herbert Hopewell,
at your service.

178
00:13:23,531 --> 00:13:25,759
Me and the Missus'll
be looking after you.

179
00:13:26,031 --> 00:13:29,097
[DAVID] Oh.Thank you,
but I can manage.

180
00:13:29,098 --> 00:13:30,996
Not while I'm still breathing.

181
00:13:31,465 --> 00:13:34,192
Reverend Richmond,
welcome to Gladbury.

182
00:13:34,431 --> 00:13:37,464
I'm Bea Haddington,
and this is my Edward.

183
00:13:37,465 --> 00:13:39,192
Edward Haddington.

184
00:13:39,630 --> 00:13:42,153
Of Haddington Chandlery.

185
00:13:42,831 --> 00:13:45,422
Home of the Christmas Candle...'!

186
00:13:46,630 --> 00:13:48,255
<i>Um.</i>

187
00:13:51,831 --> 00:13:56,092
Oh, you haven't heard of us.

188
00:13:56,664 --> 00:13:58,163
That's alright,
you'll have a chance

189
00:13:58,163 --> 00:14:00,322
to meet the reverend
soon enough.

190
00:14:00,530 --> 00:14:02,162
Lovely to see you.

191
00:14:02,163 --> 00:14:03,263
All of you!

192
00:14:03,263 --> 00:14:05,126
Let's see the church, eh?

193
00:14:07,130 --> 00:14:09,823
[church bells ring]
[organ playing]

194
00:14:13,263 --> 00:14:18,829
[ELEANOR] ♪ On a starry
night in Bethlehem, ♪

195
00:14:18,830 --> 00:14:24,329
♪ A child was born
to bring light to men. ♪

196
00:14:24,329 --> 00:14:29,762
♪ And our faith waned,
our eyes grew dim ♪

197
00:14:29,763 --> 00:14:36,529
♪ In a candle's light
we found hope again. ♪

198
00:14:36,529 --> 00:14:38,328
There are miracles
all around,

199
00:14:38,329 --> 00:14:40,028
Are you alright?

200
00:14:40,029 --> 00:14:43,517
[HERBERT] There she is,
a special soul.

201
00:14:43,962 --> 00:14:47,828
♪ Miracles yet to be found. ♪

202
00:14:47,829 --> 00:14:50,428
Sometimes I think
I'm hearing an angel.

203
00:14:50,428 --> 00:14:53,194
♪ Hid in every heart is
an answered prayer. ♪

204
00:14:53,195 --> 00:14:55,627
That's my <i>lady...</i>
Eleanor.

205
00:14:56,128 --> 00:15:03,755
♪ Like a candle': flame,
hope will lead us there. ♪

206
00:15:08,028 --> 00:15:09,660
[ELEANOR] Off with
that muddy coat!

207
00:15:09,661 --> 00:15:12,093
Did you crawl all
the way from London?

208
00:15:16,994 --> 00:15:18,294
[ELEANOR]
Come on, britches too.

209
00:15:18,295 --> 00:15:20,927
You're not the first clergyman
I've seen in his underpants.

210
00:15:20,928 --> 00:15:22,587
[Herbert laughs]

211
00:15:25,128 --> 00:15:26,923
[Eleanor giggles]

212
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:33,292
[ELEANOR]
I'll just get these cleaned up.

213
00:15:35,828 --> 00:15:37,327
[Eleanor giggles]

214
00:15:37,327 --> 00:15:40,826
We’re just across the
garden if you need us.

215
00:15:40,827 --> 00:15:42,860
Anything at all.

216
00:15:42,860 --> 00:15:45,486
Welcome to Gladbury, Reverend.

217
00:15:47,461 --> 00:15:51,793
Jesus said, "Ye are
the light of the world."

218
00:15:51,793 --> 00:15:55,859
A city that is set on
a hill cannot be hid.

219
00:15:55,860 --> 00:15:59,758
[parishioner coughs]

220
00:16:00,159 --> 00:16:05,683
Neither do men light a candle
and put it under a bushel,

221
00:16:06,293 --> 00:16:08,486
But on a candlestick.

222
00:16:08,693 --> 00:16:12,682
And it giveth light unto
all that are in the house.

223
00:16:13,926 --> 00:16:16,687
Let your light
so shine before men.

224
00:16:17,759 --> 00:16:20,492
That they may
see your good works.

225
00:16:20,492 --> 00:16:23,758
And glorify your Father,
which is in Heaven.

226
00:16:23,759 --> 00:16:25,691
Thank you Reverend.

227
00:16:27,258 --> 00:16:29,125
Is he talking about
our Christmas Candle?

228
00:16:29,126 --> 00:16:30,358
I think he's gettin' to it.

229
00:16:30,358 --> 00:16:31,756
[DAVID]
You sir!

230
00:16:31,859 --> 00:16:34,959
Would you hide this
candle under a bushel?

231
00:16:34,959 --> 00:16:36,591
No sir, I wouldn't.

232
00:16:36,592 --> 00:16:37,825
Of course not.

233
00:16:37,826 --> 00:16:40,125
And you, Mrs. Haddington?

234
00:16:40,125 --> 00:16:43,023
Would you conceal
this candle under your hat?

235
00:16:44,525 --> 00:16:46,124
Lovely as it is.

236
00:16:46,125 --> 00:16:47,818
[BEA]
No, no, never.

237
00:16:48,525 --> 00:16:51,157
[DAVID] Candles
belong on candlesticks,

238
00:16:51,158 --> 00:16:53,991
giving light to everyone.

239
00:16:53,991 --> 00:16:56,657
[DAVID]
What then is this light

240
00:16:56,658 --> 00:16:59,783
that draws men to
our Heavenly Father?

241
00:16:59,991 --> 00:17:05,855
Is it signs and wonders'!
Angels and miracles?

242
00:17:09,491 --> 00:17:11,290
[DAVID]
Of course not!

243
00:17:11,291 --> 00:17:12,357
[93335]

244
00:17:12,357 --> 00:17:16,856
[DAVID] It is our good works
that shine before men

245
00:17:16,857 --> 00:17:19,789
and glorify our
Father in Heaven.

246
00:17:22,590 --> 00:17:24,290
<i>No.</i>

247
00:17:24,291 --> 00:17:26,813
Not one word about
the Christmas Candle.

248
00:17:27,157 --> 00:17:29,452
Better luck next time.

249
00:17:30,356 --> 00:17:31,422
[LADY CAMDON]
Reverend Richmond.

250
00:17:31,423 --> 00:17:32,423
Lady Camdon.

251
00:17:32,423 --> 00:17:33,956
What a fascinating sermon.

252
00:17:33,957 --> 00:17:35,183
Thank you.

253
00:17:36,156 --> 00:17:39,356
And yet so unlike the sermons
for which you're loved.

254
00:17:39,356 --> 00:17:41,456
That's not to
worry you, Reverend.

255
00:17:41,457 --> 00:17:44,190
You'll do very
well here in Gladbury.

256
00:17:44,190 --> 00:17:46,247
I'll make sure of it.

257
00:17:51,789 --> 00:17:55,119
[DAVID] "An early Christmas gift
for you and all of Gladbury."

258
00:17:55,490 --> 00:17:57,323
This is quite unexpected.

259
00:17:57,323 --> 00:17:59,022
A gift from the
Countess of Gladbury!

260
00:17:59,023 --> 00:18:00,522
Whatever could it be?

261
00:18:00,522 --> 00:18:02,613
Whatever could it be, eh?

262
00:18:05,255 --> 00:18:08,321
Gladbury': most
beloved Advent sermons.

263
00:18:08,322 --> 00:18:09,845
Tried and true.

264
00:18:10,689 --> 00:18:13,655
[HERBERT] Some of these sermons
are two hundred years old.

265
00:18:15,489 --> 00:18:18,589
And I imagine her ladyship
expects me to use these sermons.

266
00:18:18,589 --> 00:18:21,121
Well, I can think of no
better way to preserve

267
00:18:21,122 --> 00:18:23,489
the legacy of the
Christmas Candle.

268
00:18:23,489 --> 00:18:26,322
Forgive my ignorance, but what
is this Christmas Candle?

269
00:18:26,322 --> 00:18:30,414
I think you'll find everything
you're looking for in here.

270
00:18:40,822 --> 00:18:42,515
[DAVID]
This is preposterous!

271
00:18:42,688 --> 00:18:45,245
I thought you might
stop by, Reverend.

272
00:18:45,521 --> 00:18:46,354
Tea?

273
00:18:46,354 --> 00:18:48,253
Had I known that the people
of this town were expecting

274
00:18:48,254 --> 00:18:49,754
to hear such fairy
tales from the pulpit,

275
00:18:49,755 --> 00:18:50,621
I never would have come!

276
00:18:50,621 --> 00:18:53,454
The Christmas Candle is
no fairy tale, I assure you.

277
00:18:53,455 --> 00:18:55,455
[DAVID] Oh, then I suppose
that you have seen

278
00:18:55,455 --> 00:18:57,488
this magical wish
granting angel'!

279
00:18:57,488 --> 00:18:58,612
<i>No.</i>

280
00:18:59,587 --> 00:19:01,281
But he has.

281
00:19:02,321 --> 00:19:05,653
[DAVID] Ah, yes,
the candle maker.

282
00:19:05,654 --> 00:19:07,754
Do I have some
questions for you.

283
00:19:07,754 --> 00:19:10,587
Why one Christmas Candle,
and not fifteen?

284
00:19:10,587 --> 00:19:12,820
Why doesn't this angel
come once every year?

285
00:19:12,821 --> 00:19:15,253
Or every Thursday
afternoon for tea?

286
00:19:15,253 --> 00:19:18,152
And why in all of God's
green Earth, Gladbury'!

287
00:19:18,153 --> 00:19:19,586
[EDWARD]
Why Bethlehem?

288
00:19:19,587 --> 00:19:21,486
Why a babe in a manger?

289
00:19:21,487 --> 00:19:24,520
Who could possibly hope to
understand the ways of the Lord'!

290
00:19:24,520 --> 00:19:26,419
But I see no reason to
promote superstitions

291
00:19:26,420 --> 00:19:27,420
or raise false hopes.

292
00:19:27,420 --> 00:19:30,186
[LADY CAMDON] People of
Gladbury lead difficult lives.

293
00:19:30,187 --> 00:19:33,584
Even the slightest hope of a
miracle keeps their faith alive.

294
00:19:34,153 --> 00:19:37,119
Only to be crushed when
their prayers go unanswered.

295
00:19:38,187 --> 00:19:39,519
If this is what your
people need, then I--

296
00:19:39,519 --> 00:19:41,819
[LADY CAMDON]
What our people need is hope.

297
00:19:41,820 --> 00:19:43,945
And you can give it to them.

298
00:19:44,519 --> 00:19:46,619
I know this firsthand.

299
00:19:46,619 --> 00:19:51,074
Lady Camdon, I'm not the
"miracle man" that you remember.

300
00:19:51,820 --> 00:19:54,149
Coming to Gladbury
was a mistake.

301
00:19:55,086 --> 00:19:56,919
[EDWARD] On that
we are in agreement.

302
00:19:56,919 --> 00:19:58,185
[LADY CAMDON]
But what if it were providence

303
00:19:58,186 --> 00:19:59,947
that brought you here?

304
00:20:04,119 --> 00:20:05,818
I think you should stay.

305
00:20:05,819 --> 00:20:08,119
[EDWARD]Why prolong
the inevitable?

306
00:20:08,119 --> 00:20:10,607
Just until Christmas.

307
00:20:11,351 --> 00:20:13,647
[LADY CAMDON]
This is the year.

308
00:20:14,919 --> 00:20:18,749
Please, David, consider it.

309
00:20:21,518 --> 00:20:23,609
[VICTORIA] Let's go
play in the garden.

310
00:20:24,618 --> 00:20:26,607
[BOY] Victoria, wait for me!

311
00:20:30,018 --> 00:20:32,484
[DAVID] I take it you're not
much of a horsewoman.

312
00:20:35,984 --> 00:20:37,683
[EMILY] If it isn't the
ever-helpful reverend.

313
00:20:37,684 --> 00:20:39,741
[DAVID]Well that depends
on who you're asking.

314
00:20:39,951 --> 00:20:42,318
I fear I have little to offer
the people of Gladbury.

315
00:20:42,318 --> 00:20:44,483
[EMILY] Don't pity
yourself, Reverend.

316
00:20:44,484 --> 00:20:47,416
Though I did warn you.
This town is mad.

317
00:20:48,151 --> 00:20:50,810
[DAVID] All their hopes
wrapped up in one candle.

318
00:20:51,084 --> 00:20:54,417
Oh, not just any candle,
the Christmas Candle.

319
00:20:54,417 --> 00:20:57,008
[DAVID] Miss Barstow, do I
detect an air of skepticism.

320
00:20:57,284 --> 00:20:59,250
[EMILY]The Christmas
Candle': no different than

321
00:20:59,250 --> 00:21:02,250
old wives' tales or
your Bible stories.

322
00:21:02,250 --> 00:21:04,182
Take no offense, Reverend.

323
00:21:05,683 --> 00:21:07,150
So you're not a believer then'!

324
00:21:07,150 --> 00:21:10,116
I'm a believer...
in common sense.

325
00:21:10,117 --> 00:21:14,243
If something seems too good to
be true, then most likely it is.

326
00:21:14,416 --> 00:21:16,178
They'll find out soon enough.

327
00:21:16,483 --> 00:21:19,349
In fifty years, will anyone
know what a candle is'!

328
00:21:19,349 --> 00:21:21,482
Doubtful, we've already
stepped into the

329
00:21:21,483 --> 00:21:23,483
Modern age in my father's shop,

330
00:21:23,483 --> 00:21:26,971
and I must say,
it's electrifying.

331
00:21:27,283 --> 00:21:29,316
"London Lamp 8' Electric"?

332
00:21:29,316 --> 00:21:31,416
[EMILY] The bane of Edward
Haddington': existence.

333
00:21:31,416 --> 00:21:33,748
And worse, founded
by his very own son.

334
00:21:33,749 --> 00:21:36,015
Of course.
Thomas Haddington.

335
00:21:36,016 --> 00:21:37,416
He's the Haddington':
only child,

336
00:21:37,416 --> 00:21:39,915
So the fairy tale ends with him.

337
00:21:39,916 --> 00:21:43,246
[DAVID]What's this for'!
ls this for the Christmas tree'!

338
00:21:44,416 --> 00:21:45,782
I envy him.

339
00:21:45,782 --> 00:21:47,348
He left Gladbury when
he had the chance.

340
00:21:47,348 --> 00:21:49,473
You'd be wise to do the same.

341
00:21:50,083 --> 00:21:51,776
[DAVID]
And what about you'?

342
00:21:52,016 --> 00:21:53,515
[EMILY] My time will come.

343
00:21:53,515 --> 00:21:57,447
When Father's health improves
and he can manage on his own.

344
00:21:57,682 --> 00:21:59,148
[DAVID] Perhaps
we'll find ourselves

345
00:21:59,148 --> 00:22:00,581
In London next Christmas.

346
00:22:00,582 --> 00:22:03,582
[EMILY] If you make it out
of Gladbury intact.

347
00:22:03,582 --> 00:22:07,014
♪ Oh come all ye faithful. ♪

348
00:22:07,015 --> 00:22:10,448
♪ Joyful and triumphant. ♪

349
00:22:10,449 --> 00:22:18,681
♪ Oh come ye oh come
ye to Bethlehem. ♪

350
00:22:18,681 --> 00:22:22,447
♪ Come and behold Him, ♪

351
00:22:22,448 --> 00:22:25,781
♪ Born the king of angels. ♪

352
00:22:25,781 --> 00:22:29,413
♪ Oh come let us adore Him. ♪

353
00:22:29,414 --> 00:22:33,580
♪ Oh come let us adore Him. ♪

354
00:22:33,581 --> 00:22:41,843
♪ Oh come let us adore
Him, Christ the Lord. ♪

355
00:22:41,980 --> 00:22:46,969
[citizens talking
and moving about]

356
00:22:48,947 --> 00:22:50,513
[WILLIAM] You must
be the new Reverend.

357
00:22:50,513 --> 00:22:52,411
I'm William Barstow.

358
00:22:52,780 --> 00:22:54,579
Illness kept me from
church on Sunday,

359
00:22:54,580 --> 00:22:58,580
but I've heard about you.

360
00:22:58,580 --> 00:22:59,944
Oh?

361
00:23:01,980 --> 00:23:04,646
My daughter told me the
new reverend is more

362
00:23:04,647 --> 00:23:06,847
than eager to lend
a helping hand,

363
00:23:06,847 --> 00:23:09,438
even if it does mean
wading through mud.

364
00:23:09,647 --> 00:23:12,976
Oh yes, the spirited
Miss Barstow.

365
00:23:15,346 --> 00:23:18,346
[WILLIAM] I've prayed for
something to bring

366
00:23:18,346 --> 00:23:20,445
my Emily back to the church.

367
00:23:20,446 --> 00:23:22,742
Here's hoping it's you.

368
00:23:26,946 --> 00:23:28,673
[WILLIAM] Do you
have your request?

369
00:23:28,913 --> 00:23:30,606
Go on then.

370
00:23:33,946 --> 00:23:35,912
[WILLIAM]
My nephew's a special boy.

371
00:23:35,913 --> 00:23:40,844
Lots of faith.Wants to
be a preacher, like you.

372
00:23:41,179 --> 00:23:42,512
[crowd oohs and awws]

373
00:23:42,512 --> 00:23:46,011
[EDWARD]
Ladies and gentlemen!

374
00:23:46,012 --> 00:23:52,112
Gentlefolks of Gladbury, welcome
to this very special night.

375
00:23:52,112 --> 00:23:56,411
Now feast your eyes on
the amazing, wondrous,

376
00:23:56,411 --> 00:24:01,778
mystical visions bestowed on
generations of Haddingtons.

377
00:24:01,778 --> 00:24:08,233
Gladbury': very
own Christmas Candle!

378
00:24:10,178 --> 00:24:12,511
[EDWARD]There's a story
that's been passed down

379
00:24:12,511 --> 00:24:16,603
for centuries from
father to son.

380
00:24:19,844 --> 00:24:24,177
On the first Sunday of Advent,
my great-great-great-grandfather

381
00:24:24,178 --> 00:24:26,410
was awakened by a
wondrous light.

382
00:24:26,410 --> 00:24:28,638
[WILLIAM] Poor boy's
parents died a few years back.

383
00:24:30,277 --> 00:24:32,402
We all have our stories.

384
00:24:33,144 --> 00:24:35,010
[WILLIAM] Everyone
here is holding out

385
00:24:35,011 --> 00:24:37,143
for the Christmas Candle.

386
00:24:37,143 --> 00:24:38,810
[crowd oohs and awws]

387
00:24:38,811 --> 00:24:40,610
And where's your request?

388
00:24:40,610 --> 00:24:42,476
Oh, I couldn't possibly.

389
00:24:42,477 --> 00:24:45,568
I'd much rather Charlie
receive the Candle.

390
00:24:50,410 --> 00:24:52,642
[WILLIAM]
Will you be joining us?

391
00:24:52,643 --> 00:24:56,666
[DAVID] Not tonight. I believe
I have a sermon to prepare.

392
00:24:58,177 --> 00:25:01,310
[EDWARD] And so he gave the
first Christmas Candle to orphan

393
00:25:01,310 --> 00:25:05,642
children with Gladbury':
most beloved instruction:

394
00:25:05,643 --> 00:25:08,609
light this and pray.

395
00:25:08,910 --> 00:25:11,409
[ELEANOR] ♪ Hid in every
heart is an answered prayer. ♪

396
00:25:11,409 --> 00:25:16,569
♪ Like a candle': flame,
hope will lead us there. ♪

397
00:25:18,009 --> 00:25:19,842
Yes, yes, I know the song.

398
00:25:19,842 --> 00:25:22,502
But we won't
be singing it today.

399
00:25:23,675 --> 00:25:26,342
It's the first Sunday in Advent,
we sing it every year.

400
00:25:26,342 --> 00:25:28,103
But it's tradition.

401
00:25:30,309 --> 00:25:33,608
Well, we'll just make
some new traditions, eh?

402
00:25:33,608 --> 00:25:36,972
We're just grateful we've
got a reverend in the pulpit.

403
00:25:37,442 --> 00:25:39,608
Well, I hope you
won't refuse my lady's

404
00:25:39,608 --> 00:25:42,597
other favorite
Christmas tradition.

405
00:25:46,842 --> 00:25:50,239
Gladbury': very own
Christmas Chasuble.

406
00:26:10,674 --> 00:26:12,162
Welcome.

407
00:26:13,274 --> 00:26:17,007
The first candle of Advent
is the candle of hope.

408
00:26:17,007 --> 00:26:18,939
But hope in what?

409
00:26:19,774 --> 00:26:22,607
An answered prayer? A miracle?

410
00:26:22,607 --> 00:26:24,607
A Christmas Candle?

411
00:26:24,607 --> 00:26:26,672
I'm told that tonight
marks the return

412
00:26:26,673 --> 00:26:29,173
of this remarkable tradition.

413
00:26:29,174 --> 00:26:31,571
Isn't that right Mr. Haddington?

414
00:26:33,973 --> 00:26:35,639
Yes, it is.

415
00:26:35,640 --> 00:26:37,573
[DAVID] And I'm sure
that you know this,

416
00:26:37,573 --> 00:26:43,472
But for my benefit, who here has
put in a request for the candle?

417
00:26:46,339 --> 00:26:48,138
[DAVID]Well,
surely not everyone

418
00:26:48,139 --> 00:26:50,172
can receive the
Christmas Candle.

419
00:26:50,173 --> 00:26:52,106
And yet we all have needs.

420
00:26:52,106 --> 00:26:54,231
So what hope do we have?

421
00:26:55,106 --> 00:26:57,805
Will we abandon our faith?

422
00:26:57,806 --> 00:26:59,931
Fall into despair?

423
00:27:00,473 --> 00:27:04,139
Hm'! I hope not.

424
00:27:04,139 --> 00:27:07,128
And I dare say
that we will not!

425
00:27:07,572 --> 00:27:11,838
We light this candle to remind
us that our hope does not

426
00:27:11,839 --> 00:27:15,931
come from earthly things,
but from above.

427
00:27:16,939 --> 00:27:21,305
From the God who came to us
one starry night in Bethlehem,

428
00:27:21,305 --> 00:27:23,772
and promises to
come again one day.

429
00:27:23,772 --> 00:27:26,805
And that,
good people of Gladbury,

430
00:27:26,806 --> 00:27:28,771
is miracle enough.

431
00:27:28,771 --> 00:27:31,135
[93335]

432
00:27:36,138 --> 00:27:37,271
God bless you.

433
00:27:37,272 --> 00:27:38,931
[EDWARD]
Ignore him, dear.

434
00:27:40,005 --> 00:27:44,266
Ah, Mr. Barstow. And if
it isn't the future reverend.

435
00:27:44,504 --> 00:27:48,137
I understand that we'll be
hearing your sermons one day.

436
00:27:48,138 --> 00:27:50,126
Do you have a
favorite scripture?

437
00:27:51,005 --> 00:27:52,664
Uh--

438
00:27:55,004 --> 00:27:57,402
Go on, don't be shy.

439
00:28:02,137 --> 00:28:04,270
[WILLIAM] Charlie reads
his Bible every day.

440
00:28:04,271 --> 00:28:05,634
[EMILY]
Charlie!

441
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:13,403
Poor boy would do
anything for that candle.

442
00:28:14,637 --> 00:28:15,903
[WILLIAM] Hasn't
been able to say a

443
00:28:15,904 --> 00:28:17,893
word since his parents died.

444
00:28:37,803 --> 00:28:39,636
[chaotic chatter]

445
00:28:39,636 --> 00:28:41,069
[WOMAN]
Mrs. Haddington!

446
00:28:41,070 --> 00:28:42,831
[MAN]
Take my request!

447
00:28:46,736 --> 00:28:49,002
[MAN]
Has he been yet, sir?

448
00:28:49,003 --> 00:28:51,268
What are we going to do?

449
00:28:51,269 --> 00:28:53,569
Wish the candle came
with a name attached.

450
00:28:53,569 --> 00:28:55,235
What if we already know?

451
00:28:55,235 --> 00:28:56,602
What?

452
00:28:56,602 --> 00:29:00,466
The candle.What if we
already know who should get it?

453
00:29:00,669 --> 00:29:02,430
But we can't!

454
00:29:02,736 --> 00:29:04,602
It's going to take
a miracle, Bea.

455
00:29:04,602 --> 00:29:06,968
I mean,Thomas has
been gone for ten years!

456
00:29:06,968 --> 00:29:09,763
He's not going to
come home on his own.

457
00:29:10,735 --> 00:29:14,001
Keeping the Christmas Candle
for ourselves is so selfish!

458
00:29:14,002 --> 00:29:15,468
Is it?

459
00:29:15,468 --> 00:29:17,468
I mean, think of the people.
For two hundred years,

460
00:29:17,468 --> 00:29:21,094
our family has been
alight to Gladbury.

461
00:29:21,301 --> 00:29:24,267
Does the flame go out with us?

462
00:29:25,935 --> 00:29:28,765
Keep the Christmas Candle?

463
00:29:29,301 --> 00:29:32,392
For the good of Gladbury.

464
00:29:32,934 --> 00:29:37,923
<i>♪</i>

465
00:30:19,733 --> 00:30:21,165
Edward!

466
00:30:23,766 --> 00:30:27,755
[dramatic ethereal music]

467
00:31:17,498 --> 00:31:19,487
[blast]

468
00:31:23,564 --> 00:31:25,630
Well don't look at me!
Get the candle!

469
00:31:25,631 --> 00:31:28,597
[EDWARD]
Oh yes, yes of course!

470
00:31:29,297 --> 00:31:30,957
[Edward trips]
[Bea cries out]

471
00:31:33,631 --> 00:31:35,130
[BEA]
Why, Edward!

472
00:31:35,130 --> 00:31:36,797
[EDWARD]
I couldn't see!

473
00:31:36,798 --> 00:31:38,787
It must be here somewhere.

474
00:31:38,997 --> 00:31:40,263
It must be.

475
00:31:40,264 --> 00:31:42,730
Must be here.
Where is it?

476
00:31:42,963 --> 00:31:45,725
Where is it?
Oh Edward!

477
00:31:45,930 --> 00:31:47,919
Where is it?

478
00:31:48,064 --> 00:31:49,893
Oh!

479
00:31:52,297 --> 00:31:55,922
I've lost the Christmas Candle.

480
00:31:56,963 --> 00:31:59,495
Oh surely this is
God punishing us.

481
00:31:59,496 --> 00:32:01,163
[BEA] Oh don't talk
like that, Edward.

482
00:32:01,164 --> 00:32:06,460
I was--I was foolish to
think that candle was ours.

483
00:32:24,896 --> 00:32:26,657
Is it all clear?

484
00:32:28,229 --> 00:32:30,058
[BEA]
Seems to be.

485
00:32:32,996 --> 00:32:35,427
[BEA] Edward!
The reverend is here!

486
00:32:35,629 --> 00:32:37,492
Hide the candles!

487
00:32:39,395 --> 00:32:41,328
[DAVID] Mr. Haddington.
Mrs. Haddington.

488
00:32:41,328 --> 00:32:43,123
[BEA] What a
pleasant surprise.

489
00:32:43,295 --> 00:32:45,625
[DAVID] I imagine your
night was eventful.

490
00:32:47,462 --> 00:32:49,485
So is it here?

491
00:32:52,761 --> 00:32:54,727
The Christmas Candle?

492
00:32:54,728 --> 00:32:56,161
Yes, yes it's here somewhere.

493
00:32:56,162 --> 00:32:57,162
Bea, Bea.

494
00:32:57,162 --> 00:32:58,594
Of course you're not
going to show it to me,

495
00:32:58,594 --> 00:33:00,458
but that's not why I came.

496
00:33:01,594 --> 00:33:04,393
The people's requests
for the candle...

497
00:33:04,394 --> 00:33:06,417
...may I see them?

498
00:33:13,795 --> 00:33:15,895
[BEA] What do you suppose he
intends to do with them'!

499
00:33:15,895 --> 00:33:19,088
[EDWARD]
I don't know. Pray'!

500
00:33:19,327 --> 00:33:21,589
That's what we should be doing.

501
00:33:21,761 --> 00:33:24,093
We've got to
make it better, Bea.

502
00:33:24,094 --> 00:33:25,992
Yes, but how?

503
00:33:27,428 --> 00:33:30,053
[DAVID]
All done. Thank you.

504
00:33:30,794 --> 00:33:33,660
You may have one candle
to give, but I hope to

505
00:33:33,660 --> 00:33:36,649
give everyone a little
light this Christmas.

506
00:33:36,794 --> 00:33:37,760
That's it!

507
00:33:37,760 --> 00:33:38,626
What?

508
00:33:38,627 --> 00:33:41,787
I mean... that's a lovely idea.

509
00:33:41,994 --> 00:33:43,727
Well, you mustn't delay.

510
00:33:43,727 --> 00:33:46,426
So much to be done
before Christmas.

511
00:33:46,427 --> 00:33:47,393
Good day to you.

512
00:33:47,393 --> 00:33:49,393
[BEA] Yes, yes, God speed
to you on your quest.

513
00:33:49,393 --> 00:33:51,154
What's got into you?

514
00:33:56,393 --> 00:33:59,086
We give them away. All of them.

515
00:33:59,293 --> 00:34:01,459
And have the
entire village think

516
00:34:01,460 --> 00:34:03,892
they've got the actual
Christmas Candle?

517
00:34:03,893 --> 00:34:05,126
We won't tell them that.

518
00:34:05,126 --> 00:34:06,625
We'll tell them what
this family has told

519
00:34:06,626 --> 00:34:09,456
them for generations:
to light it and pray.

520
00:34:09,626 --> 00:34:12,993
But this is Gladbury.
People talk.

521
00:34:12,993 --> 00:34:16,592
Edward, somebody':
miracle is in this basket.

522
00:34:16,592 --> 00:34:19,490
And we won't let it go to waste!

523
00:34:22,492 --> 00:34:24,124
[WILLIAM] Charlie,
the reverend has offered

524
00:34:24,125 --> 00:34:26,284
to give you Bible lessons.

525
00:34:27,159 --> 00:34:31,125
[William coughs]

526
00:34:31,125 --> 00:34:32,818
[DAVID]
Hello, Charlie.

527
00:34:33,159 --> 00:34:37,818
Why don't we start with the
Gospel of John chapter one.

528
00:34:42,391 --> 00:34:47,091
"In the beginning was the Word,
and the Word was with God,

529
00:34:47,092 --> 00:34:49,758
and the Word was God.

530
00:34:49,758 --> 00:34:52,491
The same was in
the beginning with God.

531
00:34:52,491 --> 00:34:54,624
All things were made by him;

532
00:34:54,625 --> 00:34:59,091
and without him was not any
thing made that was made.

533
00:34:59,091 --> 00:35:03,723
In him was life; and the
life was the light of men.

534
00:35:03,724 --> 00:35:06,124
And the light
shineth in darkness;

535
00:35:06,124 --> 00:35:09,920
and the darkness
comprehend it not."

536
00:35:15,924 --> 00:35:19,723
"And the impediment
to his tongue was loosed,

537
00:35:19,724 --> 00:35:22,451
and he spoke plainly."

538
00:35:24,323 --> 00:35:28,914
Now Charlie, we are going
to loose that tongue of yours.

539
00:35:29,791 --> 00:35:31,450
Open wide.

540
00:35:33,657 --> 00:35:34,986
<i>And...</i>

541
00:35:39,623 --> 00:35:41,146
[DAVID]
Very good.

542
00:35:41,457 --> 00:35:43,116
<i>And...</i>

543
00:35:47,322 --> 00:35:48,288
Louder.

544
00:35:48,756 --> 00:35:52,586
[nonsensical sounds]

545
00:36:03,889 --> 00:36:05,752
Louder.

546
00:36:22,922 --> 00:36:24,547
[knock at window]

547
00:36:29,755 --> 00:36:32,421
Light this and pray, Charlie.

548
00:36:32,422 --> 00:36:35,115
Even if it's only in your heart.

549
00:36:35,321 --> 00:36:37,150
God will hear you.

550
00:36:58,387 --> 00:37:00,253
[DAVID]
Good morning, Mr. Finch.

551
00:37:00,254 --> 00:37:02,087
What brings you to our home?

552
00:37:02,087 --> 00:37:05,087
[DAVID] I understand you
have requested the candle.

553
00:37:05,087 --> 00:37:07,985
I wondered if
I might be of service.

554
00:37:10,654 --> 00:37:12,986
Reverend, meet my family.

555
00:37:12,987 --> 00:37:14,554
My wife, Delilah.

556
00:37:14,554 --> 00:37:15,453
Hello.

557
00:37:15,454 --> 00:37:16,454
[PHINEAS]
Children.

558
00:37:16,454 --> 00:37:18,120
This is my father, Oliver.

559
00:37:18,120 --> 00:37:20,211
[OLIVER]
The new reverend!

560
00:37:20,720 --> 00:37:22,549
[PHINEAS]
Over here, Dad.

561
00:37:22,987 --> 00:37:24,384
Come on.

562
00:37:24,586 --> 00:37:26,285
Don't suppose you
could help the old man

563
00:37:26,286 --> 00:37:28,386
get his hands on the
Christmas Candle?

564
00:37:28,386 --> 00:37:30,252
Maybe put in a word
to the Haddingtons.

565
00:37:30,253 --> 00:37:31,453
[OLIVER]
Hogwash.

566
00:37:31,453 --> 00:37:33,986
The next time I see,
I hope to be

567
00:37:33,987 --> 00:37:36,252
looking at the Good
Lord himself.

568
00:37:36,253 --> 00:37:42,152
In the meantime, I'll walk
by faith, right Reverend?

569
00:37:42,620 --> 00:37:44,142
Right.

570
00:37:47,153 --> 00:37:49,453
Oh thank you.Thank you so much!

571
00:37:49,453 --> 00:37:52,044
It'll be a happy
Christmas after all!

572
00:37:52,952 --> 00:37:57,384
Remember, children,
this is our little secret.

573
00:38:19,419 --> 00:38:23,085
Reverend Richmond! Do come in.

574
00:38:23,085 --> 00:38:26,318
I've been praying for
company, Reverend.

575
00:38:26,318 --> 00:38:29,283
[DAVID] Why waste a prayer
when I can meet the need?

576
00:38:29,284 --> 00:38:33,910
So you'll find me a
knitting companion?

577
00:38:35,584 --> 00:38:39,539
<i>I... shall.</i>

578
00:38:45,117 --> 00:38:46,708
[KIDS]
Coming!

579
00:38:47,884 --> 00:38:50,484
Don't waste a candle
on an old man like me.

580
00:38:50,484 --> 00:38:54,575
Oliver, there's no such
thing as a wasted prayer.

581
00:38:57,650 --> 00:39:00,416
[MRS. BICKERTON] My stove
doesn't work, and my husband

582
00:39:00,417 --> 00:39:04,247
ran off and left me all on my
own with a colicky baby.

583
00:39:04,717 --> 00:39:08,316
Oh, and then yesterday
the wall fell down,

584
00:39:08,316 --> 00:39:10,716
and my goat left me, too.

585
00:39:10,717 --> 00:39:14,479
I shall keep an eye out...
for both of them.

586
00:39:18,717 --> 00:39:21,944
The Reverend fixing our roof.

587
00:39:22,216 --> 00:39:25,049
We so desperately need it.

588
00:39:25,050 --> 00:39:30,783
Speaking of which, Agnes, my
dumpling, hadn't you a request?

589
00:39:30,783 --> 00:39:33,874
[DAVID] Ah, yes,
Miss Agnes Chumley.

590
00:39:34,083 --> 00:39:36,708
But I see it is
an unspoken request.

591
00:39:37,382 --> 00:39:38,882
Well, go on.

592
00:39:38,883 --> 00:39:41,644
A silent request
is no request at all.

593
00:39:42,549 --> 00:39:44,749
I'm praying for a husband.

594
00:39:44,749 --> 00:39:46,873
By Easter.

595
00:40:03,249 --> 00:40:04,648
Mrs. Haddington.

596
00:40:04,648 --> 00:40:05,748
What brings you here?

597
00:40:05,748 --> 00:40:06,914
[BEA] I've come to
let you know that

598
00:40:06,915 --> 00:40:08,781
your request has been heard.

599
00:40:08,782 --> 00:40:11,805
Oh what a dear,
but I couldn't accept.

600
00:40:11,982 --> 00:40:15,573
That handsome young
reverend has been helping me.

601
00:40:18,748 --> 00:40:20,407
[BEA]
I see.

602
00:40:31,214 --> 00:40:37,305
[BEA] Agnes, dear,
light this and pray.

603
00:40:41,480 --> 00:40:43,071
Mother!

604
00:40:44,081 --> 00:40:46,376
It's the devil's work!

605
00:40:48,614 --> 00:40:50,213
[WIDOW LEONARD]
You tell her, Reverend.

606
00:40:50,213 --> 00:40:51,613
It's unnatural.

607
00:40:51,614 --> 00:40:52,879
What'!

608
00:40:52,880 --> 00:40:54,710
Ungodly.

609
00:40:55,647 --> 00:40:57,135
Yes.

610
00:40:59,414 --> 00:41:01,080
[DAVID] And the light
shineth in Gladbury,

611
00:41:01,080 --> 00:41:02,913
and yet the people
comprehend it not.

612
00:41:02,913 --> 00:41:03,746
[Emily laughs]

613
00:41:03,746 --> 00:41:06,579
[EMILY] Make fun all you want,
you've decided to stay here.

614
00:41:06,579 --> 00:41:08,807
Just long enough
to do some good.

615
00:41:09,280 --> 00:41:11,472
I have a letter
to post for London.

616
00:41:12,646 --> 00:41:16,779
Ruth Goodchild.
To a lady no less.

617
00:41:16,780 --> 00:41:17,946
[DAVID]
Yes, she's a guest of the

618
00:41:17,946 --> 00:41:20,478
Salvation Army in a
difficult situation.

619
00:41:20,479 --> 00:41:22,468
She's just a girl really.

620
00:41:23,879 --> 00:41:26,811
Stockings. Sweets.

621
00:41:29,879 --> 00:41:31,446
May I help you?

622
00:41:31,446 --> 00:41:36,639
I'm looking for, well, uh,
a lot of things actually.

623
00:41:37,912 --> 00:41:39,378
[EMILY]
Sardines.

624
00:41:39,545 --> 00:41:40,878
Thank you.

625
00:41:40,879 --> 00:41:42,435
Soap.

626
00:41:44,578 --> 00:41:45,611
String.

627
00:41:45,612 --> 00:41:47,079
It's alphabetical.

628
00:41:47,079 --> 00:41:48,244
I see.

629
00:41:48,245 --> 00:41:50,445
[DAVID] Well, to do much,
one must be organized.

630
00:41:50,445 --> 00:41:53,611
You really do want to
help these people, don't you'!

631
00:41:53,612 --> 00:41:55,407
Of course I do.

632
00:41:56,478 --> 00:42:00,739
[church organ]

633
00:42:02,378 --> 00:42:03,877
[DAVID]
Welcome everyone.

634
00:42:03,878 --> 00:42:08,144
We light the second candle
of Advent in the love of God.

635
00:42:08,145 --> 00:42:10,477
During Advent,
God pierces the darkness

636
00:42:10,477 --> 00:42:13,637
of the world with
divine light and love.

637
00:42:15,477 --> 00:42:20,637
Because he loved us, he sent
his son to light the way.

638
00:42:21,778 --> 00:42:24,539
Though we must wait
for Christmas day,

639
00:42:25,711 --> 00:42:29,644
we must not wait to love
one another as Christ did.

640
00:42:29,644 --> 00:42:32,973
Does your neighbor need
a miracle this Christmas?

641
00:42:34,244 --> 00:42:36,876
Well why not be that miracle?

642
00:42:36,877 --> 00:42:38,309
[mumbling in crowd]

643
00:42:40,576 --> 00:42:41,974
[MR. COLLINS]
Reverend!

644
00:42:42,710 --> 00:42:43,810
Hello Mr. Collins.

645
00:42:43,810 --> 00:42:45,409
Thought maybe
you could use a hand.

646
00:42:45,410 --> 00:42:48,138
You know, "be the miracle."

647
00:42:49,144 --> 00:42:54,132
<i>♪</i>

648
00:42:56,376 --> 00:42:57,706
[DAVID] Ow.

649
00:42:58,076 --> 00:42:59,974
Where did he come from?

650
00:43:06,942 --> 00:43:08,374
[EDWARD]
Reverend.

651
00:43:08,543 --> 00:43:11,309
[BEA]
Happy candle. Christmas!

652
00:43:11,309 --> 00:43:12,641
[DAVID]
And to you.

653
00:43:12,642 --> 00:43:14,075
[EDWARD]Why'd you
have to say that. Come on.

654
00:43:14,076 --> 00:43:15,905
[BEA]
I'm so sorry.

655
00:43:23,242 --> 00:43:25,401
[DAVID]The prodigal
goat has returned.

656
00:43:26,442 --> 00:43:28,067
Thank you.

657
00:43:28,742 --> 00:43:30,475
Oh, you won't believe it!

658
00:43:30,475 --> 00:43:33,407
The neighbors are
building me a new wall.

659
00:43:47,875 --> 00:43:49,704
[metal clanging]

660
00:43:54,474 --> 00:43:55,607
Here he comes.

661
00:43:55,608 --> 00:43:57,301
Shh.

662
00:44:08,408 --> 00:44:10,601
[metal clanging]

663
00:44:18,907 --> 00:44:20,107
[DAVID]
How does it feel?

664
00:44:20,107 --> 00:44:24,272
Feels... it feels
a lot like seeing!

665
00:44:24,273 --> 00:44:27,967
See Reverend, you
are a miracle worker.

666
00:44:30,140 --> 00:44:31,766
[DAVID]
Hello.

667
00:44:34,240 --> 00:44:35,707
That's a lot of food, Reverend.

668
00:44:35,707 --> 00:44:38,036
Well, you have a
lot of mouths to feed.

669
00:44:40,206 --> 00:44:42,069
That's beautiful.

670
00:44:43,073 --> 00:44:45,096
Another visitor, I--

671
00:44:45,607 --> 00:44:46,706
Hello everyone.

672
00:44:46,706 --> 00:44:50,264
[DAVID] Um,Widow Leonard
just brought us a feast!

673
00:44:50,539 --> 00:44:53,072
Please,join us Reverend.

674
00:44:53,073 --> 00:44:54,561
[DAVID]
Why not?

675
00:44:59,472 --> 00:45:01,271
[WIDOW LEONARD]
I know we fast during Advent

676
00:45:01,272 --> 00:45:03,605
and save the feasting
for Christmas day,

677
00:45:03,606 --> 00:45:08,766
but having company,
that's like Christmas to me.

678
00:45:09,439 --> 00:45:11,802
Gladbury': Christmas pudding.

679
00:45:14,872 --> 00:45:16,532
[BEA]
Light this and pray.

680
00:45:23,139 --> 00:45:26,128
[EDWARD]
Light this and pray.

681
00:45:55,971 --> 00:46:32,869
[prayers spoken aloud,
fading in and out]

682
00:46:32,870 --> 00:46:33,460
[VOICE]
Amen.

683
00:46:33,636 --> 00:46:34,193
[VOICE]
Amen.

684
00:46:34,770 --> 00:46:36,031
[GROUP]
Amen.

685
00:46:36,903 --> 00:46:39,302
[DAVID] Rejoice,
for today we light

686
00:46:39,302 --> 00:46:41,402
the third candle of Advent,

687
00:46:41,403 --> 00:46:43,392
the candle of joy.

688
00:46:47,136 --> 00:46:52,302
When Christ was born,
God used angels to proclaim

689
00:46:52,302 --> 00:46:54,634
"good tidings of great joy."

690
00:46:54,635 --> 00:46:57,068
To all mankind.

691
00:46:57,069 --> 00:47:00,728
Now, we are the messengers
of this good news.

692
00:47:01,869 --> 00:47:05,401
For with every good deed,
every act of kindness,

693
00:47:05,402 --> 00:47:09,096
Christ is born again
and again in our lives.

694
00:47:09,535 --> 00:47:13,768
Now let us go forth,
as joyful messengers,

695
00:47:13,769 --> 00:47:15,961
doing the work of God.

696
00:47:21,135 --> 00:47:23,901
Your work in this town is
impressive, Reverend Richmond.

697
00:47:23,901 --> 00:47:24,967
Thank you, Lady Camdon.

698
00:47:24,968 --> 00:47:27,634
Still there are limits
to what man can do.

699
00:47:27,634 --> 00:47:29,401
[MRS. CHUMLEY]
Reverend. Reverend.

700
00:47:29,402 --> 00:47:30,390
Mrs. Chumley.

701
00:47:31,035 --> 00:47:32,466
Miss Chumley.

702
00:47:32,968 --> 00:47:36,593
How lovely to see
a sister in the Lord.

703
00:47:36,734 --> 00:47:38,967
Well go on my dear,
what have you to say?

704
00:47:38,968 --> 00:47:41,467
I've already made my wishes
known to the Reverend.

705
00:47:41,467 --> 00:47:44,025
And now I'm taking
a step of faith.

706
00:47:45,234 --> 00:47:46,928
Thank you.

707
00:47:52,567 --> 00:47:54,866
[DAVID] Another prayer that
will never be answered.

708
00:47:54,867 --> 00:47:56,766
Well, I for one am
happy to see that

709
00:47:56,767 --> 00:47:58,434
In spite of all your efforts,

710
00:47:58,434 --> 00:48:02,593
you are still inspiring
hope for a miracle.

711
00:48:13,233 --> 00:48:15,199
Come in.

712
00:48:16,800 --> 00:48:18,299
[DAVID]
Mrs. Hopewell.

713
00:48:18,299 --> 00:48:20,532
A friend of mine may be
coming to Gladbury for a while.

714
00:48:20,533 --> 00:48:22,299
I wondered if she might
stay with you and Herbert.

715
00:48:22,299 --> 00:48:23,732
[ELEANOR] She can stay
as long as she likes.

716
00:48:23,733 --> 00:48:25,265
[DAVID] Thank you!
Her name's Ruth.

717
00:48:25,266 --> 00:48:27,698
My colleague Abner
will bring her from London.

718
00:48:28,466 --> 00:48:30,193
Oh, please, allow me.

719
00:48:30,400 --> 00:48:31,932
[ELEANOR]
This is no job for a reverend.

720
00:48:31,932 --> 00:48:32,898
[DAVID]
Nonsense.

721
00:48:32,899 --> 00:48:34,865
[ELEANOR]
This is no job for a lady.

722
00:48:35,565 --> 00:48:38,929
Mrs. Hopewell.
Whatever is the matter?

723
00:48:39,365 --> 00:48:41,099
No, I won't do it.

724
00:48:41,099 --> 00:48:44,431
[DOCTOR] Herbert, you're one
good shock away from the grave.

725
00:48:44,432 --> 00:48:46,065
I'll get plenty of
rest in Heaven.

726
00:48:46,066 --> 00:48:47,032
Herbert.

727
00:48:47,033 --> 00:48:48,766
[DOCTOR] Which
may not be that far off.

728
00:48:48,766 --> 00:48:50,532
You've got a weak heart.

729
00:48:50,532 --> 00:48:52,465
I have a strong faith.

730
00:48:52,465 --> 00:48:55,298
God will either cure me,
or He'll call me home.

731
00:48:55,298 --> 00:48:57,564
[ELEANOR] Of course
he will, but you have to rest.

732
00:48:57,565 --> 00:48:59,197
[DOCTOR] No more
carrying heavy boxes,

733
00:48:59,198 --> 00:49:00,964
climbing ladders,
or chopping wood.

734
00:49:00,965 --> 00:49:01,965
Do you hear me?

735
00:49:01,965 --> 00:49:04,090
But that's my job!

736
00:49:04,232 --> 00:49:05,798
I will chop the wood.

737
00:49:05,798 --> 00:49:08,798
No. No m'lady, I won't have it.

738
00:49:08,798 --> 00:49:11,064
Please. Pray for him, Reverend.

739
00:49:11,065 --> 00:49:12,758
[DAVID]
Certainly.

740
00:49:13,698 --> 00:49:17,131
Our Father in Heaven, please
grant your servant Herbert with

741
00:49:17,132 --> 00:49:18,598
the good sense to follow the

742
00:49:18,598 --> 00:49:22,121
doctor's orders and
get some rest.

743
00:49:26,798 --> 00:49:28,063
[DAVID] I've had
enough of Herbert

744
00:49:28,064 --> 00:49:29,397
hauling crates of candles.

745
00:49:29,398 --> 00:49:32,464
Besides, it's high time
that Gladbury see the light.

746
00:49:32,464 --> 00:49:36,263
[EMILY] Electricity...
In the church.

747
00:49:36,264 --> 00:49:38,630
For too long the church has
stumbled about in the dark ages,

748
00:49:38,630 --> 00:49:40,863
when it should
be lighting the way.

749
00:49:40,864 --> 00:49:42,364
In fact, I believe that
the church should

750
00:49:42,364 --> 00:49:45,386
be the first place to
embrace the future.

751
00:49:45,764 --> 00:49:48,930
Indeed. Now this I have to see.

752
00:49:48,930 --> 00:49:51,030
[DAVID] Miss Barstow,
does this mean that you'll

753
00:49:51,031 --> 00:49:53,031
finally be coming to church?

754
00:49:53,031 --> 00:49:55,196
[Emily laughs]

755
00:49:55,196 --> 00:49:57,355
Twenty-nine prayers.

756
00:49:57,530 --> 00:49:59,263
And only one can be answered.

757
00:49:59,263 --> 00:50:04,263
You mean thirty, dear.
Thirty candles.

758
00:50:04,263 --> 00:50:05,895
No, I'm certain
there were twenty-nine.

759
00:50:05,896 --> 00:50:07,862
[EDWARD] Bea, there were
thirty candles hanging

760
00:50:07,863 --> 00:50:09,596
the night of the angel's visit.

761
00:50:09,596 --> 00:50:11,960
There're always thirty candles.

762
00:50:14,063 --> 00:50:15,529
Twenty-nine!

763
00:50:15,529 --> 00:50:17,428
Bea, a candle is--

764
00:50:17,429 --> 00:50:20,929
Don't say it Edward,
please don't say it out loud.

765
00:50:20,929 --> 00:50:24,089
We've lost the candle.

766
00:50:25,095 --> 00:50:28,892
[hammering and voices]

767
00:50:34,795 --> 00:50:37,861
I'm curious to know the maximum
number you've ever installed.

768
00:50:37,862 --> 00:50:39,260
[ELECTRICIAN]
About twenty.

769
00:50:39,596 --> 00:50:41,289
[DAVID]
Then I want thirty.

770
00:50:41,762 --> 00:50:43,955
No, thirty-five bulbs.

771
00:50:44,595 --> 00:50:46,362
I question the safety of it.

772
00:50:46,362 --> 00:50:48,594
The circuit can only support
so many watts, Reverend.

773
00:50:48,595 --> 00:50:51,461
[DAVID] Then install another
circuit. Install five circuits.

774
00:50:51,461 --> 00:50:53,294
I want the light in
this church to surpass

775
00:50:53,294 --> 00:50:56,460
the brightness of one
thousand candles.

776
00:50:56,461 --> 00:50:58,794
[HERBERT] Reverend Richmond,
could you tell me why

777
00:50:58,795 --> 00:51:01,960
there are men digging
in the church yard,

778
00:51:01,961 --> 00:51:04,553
and fiddling in
our sanctuary walls.

779
00:51:05,795 --> 00:51:08,294
You leave that. My grandfather
carved that altar.

780
00:51:08,294 --> 00:51:13,783
[DAVID] Herbert! I ordered them
here to install electricity.

781
00:51:14,927 --> 00:51:16,093
Electricity?

782
00:51:16,094 --> 00:51:18,227
Electricity is the future.

783
00:51:18,228 --> 00:51:19,627
And a more
practical one at that.

784
00:51:19,627 --> 00:51:20,727
Practical you say'!

785
00:51:20,727 --> 00:51:24,227
How will our treasury
stand this extravagance?

786
00:51:24,228 --> 00:51:26,760
Don't trouble yourself,
Mr. Hopewell.

787
00:51:26,761 --> 00:51:29,057
I've covered the
cost personally.

788
00:51:29,293 --> 00:51:30,960
Consider it my contribution to a

789
00:51:30,961 --> 00:51:33,694
brighter chapter of
Gladbury': history.

